\begin{center}
	\textbf{Qn:} Consider a Particle Whose wave function is given by $\psi(w) = Ae^{-a{x}^{2}}$ . What is the value of A if the wave function is normalized?
\end{center}
\begin{center}
	Solution
\end{center}
\begin{center}

To normalize the \textit{function},
	we integrate from +infinity to -negative infinity = 1
	\par from $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}|\psi(w)|d{x}$ = 1
	\newline
		\newline but $\psi(w) = Ae^{-a{x}^{2}}$
		\newline
		\newline $|\psi(w)|^{2}| = A^{2}e^{-2(a{x}^{2})}$
		\newline
		\newline $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}A^{2}e^{-2(a{x}^{2})}$ = 1
		\newline
		\newline $A^{2}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{-2(a{x}^{2})}$ = 1
		\newline
		\newline let $2{x}^{2}  = y^2$ 
		\newline
		\newline s.t $y = \sqrt{2a}{x}$
		\newline
		\newline $d{x} = \frac{d{y})}{2a}$
		\newline
\newline$\frac{A^2)}{\sqrt{2a}}\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{-y^{2}}dy = 1$
\newline
\newline $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{-y^{2}}dy=  \frac{A^2}{\sqrt{2a}} $
\newline
\newline \textbf{But From The integral Table}  $\int_{-\infty}^{\infty}e^{-y^{2}}dy= \pi $
\newline
\newline therefore $\pi = \frac{A^2}{\sqrt{2a}}$
\newline
\newline $ {A^2} = \frac{\sqrt{2a}}{A^2}$
\newline
\newline thus $ A = (\frac{\sqrt{2a}}{\pi})^\frac{1}{2}$
\newline
\end{center}



	
	
